  "text": "Previous findings in H10 cells 7 suggest that NDPK B/G␤␥mediated phosphate transfer is a mechanism for receptorindependent G protein activation. Here we studied the effect of a His to Leu replacement at position 266 in G␤ 1 on NDPK B/G␤␥-mediated G s activation, using cAMP as reporter. Experiments were performed in H10-WT cells and H10 cells with a 3-fold overexpression of NDPK B (NDPKϩ cells 7 ). cAMP production was determined in the presence of the ␤-adrenoceptor (␤AR) inverse agonist propranolol to block spontaneous or constitutive ␤AR activity. Infection of H10 cells with increasing doses of AdG␣ s combined with either AdG␤ 1 WT␥ 2 or AdG␤ 1 H266L␥ 2 resulted in similar amounts of protein expression ( Figure 2A ). Overexpression of the G␤ 1 ␥ 2 variants did not alter of NDPK B expression ( Figure 2A ) nor the total NDPK activity in these cells (GFP: 93.7Ϯ4.3, G␤ 1 WT␥ 2 : 90.5Ϯ3.6, G␤ 1 H266L␥ 2 : 91.7Ϯ4.3 nmol/min*mg). In H10-WT cells, increasing amounts of G␣ s were associated with a linear increase cAMP accumulation. However, coexpression of G␤ 1 H266L␥ 2 reduced this effect by Ϸ30% compared with G␤ 1 WT␥ 2 at each level of G␣ s ( Figure 2B ). In NDPKϩ cells, the elevated NDPK B content increased the G␣ s -mediated cAMP synthesis [CITATION_1] and enhanced the inhibitory effect of G␤ 1 H266L␥ 2 ( Figure 2C ). At the highest G␣ s expression (MOI 100), the cAMP content in G␤ 1 H266L␥ 2 -infected NDPKϩ cells amounted to 45.0Ϯ3.7% (nϭ4, PϽ0.001) of that seen in G␤ 1 WT␥ 2 -infected cells. Thus, the observed difference between G␤ 1 WT␥ 2 and G␤ 1 H266L␥ 2 overexpressing cells in basal cAMP synthesis apparently depends on both the level of G␣ s and NDPK B.",
